#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:5
msgid "Remote work options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:9
msgid ""
"Remote work offers Africans a fairer opportunity to compete in a global "
"jobs market."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:11
msgid "Different kinds of remote"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:13
msgid ""
"Many companies around the world advertise remote jobs, but not all remote"
" jobs are the same kind of remote. It's possible to waste a lot of time "
"looking through job advertisements, and even applying for them, because "
"the listings don't make it completely clear what's required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:18
msgid "Contribute your perspective"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:20
msgid ""
"Do you work remotely for an international employer What has your "
"experience been?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:22
msgid ":ref:`How to contribute <contribute>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:26
msgid "Globally remote versus working from home"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:28
msgid ""
"Be aware that many jobs are advertised as remote, and on inspection it "
"turns out that they really they just mean \"working from home\" in a "
"particular country or even state. (US-based companies are particularly "
"prone to this, as if they forget sometimes that other countries exist.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:30
msgid ""
"Sometimes a company is able to hire people across the world, but only in "
"particular countries (where for example they have an office or are "
"represented by an agency)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:32
msgid ""
"*Globally remote* generally does mean anywhere in the world, though there"
" will likely be some constraints on hiring in certain countries. For "
"example, international sanctions, or just logistical difficulties, mean "
"that it can be very difficult to get payment through to employees in some"
" countries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:34
msgid "A particular job might have a time zone requirement:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:36
msgid "EMEA: Europe, Middle East, Africa"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:37
msgid "APAC: Asia-Pacific"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:38
msgid "AMER: Americas"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:40
msgid ""
"If that's the case, it's probably a hard requirement, and for an African "
"living in Africa only jobs in EMEA are likely to be suitable. But, "
"someone at the edge of West Africa or East Africa might just be "
"considered for a job in AMEA or APAC respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:44
msgid "Employment arrangements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:47
msgid "Employee or contractor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:49
msgid ""
"An employer isn't just a company that hands over money in exchange for "
"work. It's a legal arrangement. In most countries, an employer must be a "
"legal entity in that country, pay local taxes on your salary, meet legal "
"requirements (like having employer's insurance) and so on. Almost no "
"companies are so large and globally wide-spread that they can do this for"
" every country."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:51
msgid ""
"In many cases, the actual legal arrangement that will hold is between a "
"company and a *contractor* (*i.e.* you). You will have a contract to do "
"work, but you won't formally be employed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:53
msgid ""
"You might in certain countries be required to set up your own contracting"
" company, that works for the remote employer, and employs you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:55
msgid ""
"Or, there might be an arrangement with a local agency that acts on behalf"
" of the employer, and through which you receive your pay (:ref:`remote-"
"outsourcing`, below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:57
msgid ""
"These arrangements are more complex than simply being employed, and you "
"also have fewer rights, but a respectable employer will make decent "
"efforts to ensure that you enjoy fair treatment and are not a second-"
"class kind of employee."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:63
msgid "Outsourcing arrangements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:67
msgid ""
"You **must** seek and take notice of other people's experience with "
"particular outsourcing companies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:69
msgid ""
"In an outsourcing arrangement, a company - sometimes itself a global "
"company or one covering a large global region, or one dedicated to a "
"particular country - helps another company meets its staffing needs by "
"handling the logistics of employing people in other countries. There are "
"good ones, that have been the foundation for real, sustainable careers, "
"and there are some exploitative ones. Do your research."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:72
msgid ""
"Outsourcing companies are in fact not just for remote workers - some will"
" also provide office space and facilities, and some outsourcing means "
"working in a local office with colleagues, all dedicated to serving the "
"the same foreign company."
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:76
msgid "Freelance agencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../remote-work-options.rst:78
msgid ""
"Another arrangement is a freelancing agency, a company that has a pool of"
" engineers and other software professionals on their books, for temporary"
" contracts. It's a different kind of relationship, better suited to the "
"seasoned professional who is able to step into an unknown context and "
"begin contributing almost immediately than to a junior."
msgstr ""

